{"team": "warriors", "url": "https://www.nba.com/warriors/news-blogs/warriors-classics-2017finals-game1-20200413", "date": "2020-04-13 00:00:00", "tags": ["Warriors", "GSW History"], "article": " Concerns over the spread of COVID-19 have impacted our everyday lives throughout Dub Nation. As we navigate this unprecedented situation together, the Warriors want to share some feel-good content in the midst of these uncertain times. The Warriors were back in the NBA Finals for the third consecutive year, and for a record-breaking third consecutive time they were facing the Cleveland Cavaliers for the title. It was a highly anticipated rematch as the Warriors, who defeated Cleveland in 2015 for the NBA Championship, were upset by the Cavaliers after the Warriors held a 3-1 series lead in 2016. But this year, the Dubs returned the Finals with the addition of former MVP Kevin Durant, who had signed with the club in the weeks following the Warriors\u2019 loss to the Cavs in 2016. The Warriors were undefeated through the first three rounds of the 2017 NBA Playoffs, but could they keep up the momentum against their rivals from the Eastern Conference? Would the presence of Durant be enough to tip the scales in the Dubs\u2019 favor to take the rubber-match between these two teams? If Game 1 of the 2017 Finals was any indication, it was going to be one electric series.  It started as a tightly contested first half, but Andre Iguodala ended it with a bang with a three-pointer at the buzzer, giving the Dubs a 60-52 lead at the half and appropriately signifying what was to come. @andre ending the first quarter in style. #BeforeTheLight A post shared by  Golden State Warriors (@warriors) on Jun 1, 2017 at 7:04pm PDT The Warriors poured on the points when they entered the third quarter as Curry, Durant, and Zaza Pachulia fueled a 13-0 run over the first four minutes of the frame. The 21-point lead the squad generated would prove to be insurmountable for the Cavaliers, despite a 28-point, 15-rebound, eight-assist effort from LeBron James When all was said and done, the Warriors captured Game 1 of the 2017 Finals 113-91 on their home court in Oakland. The win was their 13th straight in the playoffs, tying the Los Angeles Lakers from 1988 and 1989 in the record books for the longest postseason winning streak in NBA history. Kevin Durant was a force throughout, leading all scorers with 38 points to go along with eight rebounds and eight assists. Stephen Curry sank six three-pointers on his way to a double-double with 28 points and 10 assists. It was an emotional night as the Warriors took their first step to eventually claiming their second title in three years and Dub Nation saw the return of Steve Kerr as the Dubs head coach while rehabbing from a lingering back issue. Take a listen to the sounds of the night with the latest Warriors Sound Podcast. You will now recieve Warriors Insider emails! Please check your inbox for a confirmation message We received an error message while processing your submission. Please make sure all the fields are filled out correctly and try again. "}
{"team": "warriors", "url": "https://www.nba.com/warriors/news-blogs/warriors-sound-2017-finals-game-3-20200415", "date": "2020-04-15 00:00:00", "tags": ["Warriors", "Warriors Sound", "GSW History"], "article": " Concerns over the spread of COVID-19 have impacted our everyday lives throughout Dub Nation. As we navigate this unprecedented situation together, the Warriors want to share some feel-good content in the midst of these uncertain times. Game 3 of the 2017 NBA Finals was a memorable night in Cleveland as Kevin Durant drained an unforgettable three-pointer with under a minute to play, propelling the Warriors to a 3-0 lead over the Cavaliers in what was the team's 15th postseason victory, marking the most consecutive wins in NBA playoff history. The 118-113 win on the road was fueled by Durant\u2019s team-high 31 points while Stephen Curry added 26 points and 13 rebounds. Klay Thompson who had 30 points, including six three-pointers, joined Tim Roye and Jim Barnett on the Warriors Radio Network as Curry spoke with Marc Stein on ESPN Radio after the game. The Warriors would eventually hoist the Larry O\u2019Brien trophy in front of the home fans in the Bay Area, but this night in Ohio was certainly key on the way to the 2017 title. You will now recieve Warriors Insider emails! Please check your inbox for a confirmation message We received an error message while processing your submission. Please make sure all the fields are filled out correctly and try again. "}
